#The Visualization For my visualization I want to use a ggplot to make a simple chart over the reign period of the Danish Monarchs. The chart I want to create is with the name of the monarch on the x axis and the time of their reign on the y axis.

ggplot(data = monarchs,
       aes(x = name,
           y = reign_period)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (`position_stack()`).

#Second Try

This chart is showing what I told it to do, but it is very cramped, which is why I want to make another chart which is more readable and easy on the eye. That why I added the theme and choose to make the angle of the names on the x axis 45 degrees to make it more readable.

ggplot(data = monarchs,
       aes(x = name,
           y = reign_period)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (`position_stack()`).

#Third try

My second try still looks cramped, but its better. Therefore I wanted to make the last try with just the monarchs who have reigned for the longest period. Here I made another dataframe called top_monarchs where I choose the ones who reign the longest. Afterwards I made a new chart only with the top_monarchs dataframe and still chose to angle the names on the x axis because it made it more readable.

library(dplyr)

top_monarchs <- monarchs %>%
  arrange(desc(reign_period)) %>%
  top_n(n = 10)
## Selecting by reign_period
ggplot(data = top_monarchs,
       aes(x = name,
           y = reign_period)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
